 - paper title: Physics opportunities of a 100 TeV proton–proton collider
 - abstract: Abstract   The discovery of the Higgs boson at the LHC exposes some of the most profound mysteries fundamental physics has encountered in decades, opening the door to the next phase of experimental exploration. More than ever, this will necessitate new machines to push us deeper into the energy frontier. In this article, we discuss the physics motivation and present the physics potential of a proton–proton collider running at an energy significantly beyond that of the LHC and a luminosity comparable to that of the LHC. 100 TeV is used as a benchmark of the center of mass energy, with integrated luminosities of    3       ab     −  1    –  30       ab     −  1     .
 - publication date: 2016-10-01
 - venue: Physics Reports

